            <translation>
               But elsewhere he says: 1000, 10000, etc.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian" method="pen">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="intext">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Vnica[e]:charatti Vnica[e]  
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                Twelfths. Carats. Twelfths. <!-- DO: Not sure how to translate this either. 'Unciae' is 'twelfths' or 'of the tweflth' and all I can find for 'charatti' is that 'charattus' might be 'carat'. --> <!-- JG: charattus is also known as siliqua, see: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1686184/-->
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian" method="pen">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="intext">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Vna Vncia co[n]tinet charattos 144:   
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>One twelfth contains 144 carats.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian" method="pen">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="tail">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Qua[n]titate[m] vtriusq[ue] Metalli h√Æc co[m]mixti semper supponit esse Marcam, id est, vncias octo: scilicet charattos 1152. 
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                He supposes that quantity of both metals mixed here always is a mark [=a measure of weight], that is, 8/12, which is, naturally, 1152 carats. 
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
